## Domain Package Shape

Every domain generated by `go-scaffold generate module <name>` looks
like this ‚Äî copy the shape by hand if you ever add one without the CLI:

```text
internal/app/<domain>/
‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ model/             # domain model(s) + GORM table(s) ‚Äî a folder, one file per table
‚îÇ   ‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ model.go
‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ dto.go             # request/response structs + mapping (never leak the model directly)
‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ errors.go          # domain error catalog (<DOMAIN>_NOT_FOUND, ...)
‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ repository.go       # the only place that touches the DB for this domain, every method takes ctx
‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ service.go          # business logic; declares the repository interface it needs (mockable in tests)
‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ handler.go          # HTTP: routing, bind, delegate, respond
‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ service_test.go     # unit test, fake repo, no DB
‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ handler_test.go     # integration test, real Postgres, transaction rolled back per test
```

### Model

- Lives in its own `model` subpackage (`internal/app/<domain>/model`), imported
  by the rest of the domain as `model.<Type>`
- A folder, not a single file, so a domain with more than one table (e.g.
  `order` + `order_item`) adds one file per table instead of growing a single
  file ‚Äî `generate module` only ever creates the first one
- Every consumer inside `cmd/api/main.go` imports each domain's `model`
  package under an alias (`ordermodel`, `usermodel`, ...) since they all share
  the package name `model`

## Layer Conventions

### Handler
- Owns routing, request binding, and calling the service
- No business logic ‚Äî `c.Error(err); return` on failure, nothing more
- Reads pagination via `pagination.Parse(c)`, wraps list responses with
  `p.Response(out)`
- Reads the `:id` param via `httpx.ParseID(c)`

### Service
- Contains the business logic, knows nothing about HTTP
- Declares a `repository` interface for what it needs from the data layer ‚Äî
  this is what makes it mockable in `service_test.go` without a DB
- Generates the ID itself via `id.New()` before calling `repository.Create`
- Maps DB errors to domain errors with `dberr.IsDuplicate` /
  `dberr.IsForeignKey`, never lets a raw DB error escape

### Repository
- The only file per domain that talks to GORM
- Every method takes `ctx context.Context` first, so a cancelled request
  cancels the query
- Look up by ID with an explicit `"id = ?"` ‚Äî the PK is a UUID, not an int,
  and GORM can misinterpret a bare struct arg

### DTOs
- `createInput`/`updateInput` (request, `binding:` tags) and `response`
  (what's actually sent back) are separate types from the model ‚Äî adding a
  DB column later doesn't leak it to clients until you decide to

### Error Catalog
- One function per error, not a shared `var` ‚Äî the error middleware writes
  the request ID onto the returned pointer, so a shared instance would race
  across concurrent requests
- Codes are domain-specific (`ORDER_NOT_FOUND`), never the generic
  `apperror.NewNotFound()` directly from a handler

## Domains With a Foreign Key (Relations) ‚Äî 3 Rules

The CLI does not scaffold relations between domains; when you add one by
hand, follow these three rules (see `internal/app/order` for a worked example
if this project has one):

1. **Reference by ID column only** (`UserID uuid.UUID`). No GORM
   associations / belongs-to ‚Äî that's what keeps one domain package from
   importing another.
2. **Declare the FK constraint in migration SQL**
   (`REFERENCES ... ON DELETE ...`), not a GORM tag ‚Äî AutoMigrate doesn't
   create the constraint, which would make dev and prod schemas diverge.
3. **Map the FK error to the right status** via `dberr.IsForeignKey` ‚Äî
   inserting a reference to a missing parent, or deleting a parent that
   still has children, is a client error (409/422), not a 500. Don't
   pre-check existence before insert; let the DB enforce it atomically and
   catch the error ‚Äî a pre-check has a TOCTOU race.

## Calling Another Domain's Logic

For behavior, not just a data reference (e.g. `order` needs `user`'s email
to put on a receipt) ‚Äî the caller's `service.go` declares its own narrow
interface for exactly what it needs, the same way it already declares a
`repository` interface:

```go
// order/service.go
type userLookup interface {
    GetByID(ctx context.Context, id uuid.UUID) (user.Response, error)
}
```

`cmd/api/main.go` wires the concrete `user` service in ‚Äî it already
satisfies the interface, no adapter needed:

```go
userSvc := user.NewService(userRepo)
orderSvc := order.NewService(orderRepo, userSvc)
```

- **One direction only.** If `user` would need to call back into `order`,
  don't wire it both ways ‚Äî either the two belong in one domain, or the
  callback needs an event/queue, not a direct call.
- **Don't use this to replace a FK check.** Calling `userLookup.GetByID`
  to verify a user exists before inserting an order is the same TOCTOU race
  rule 3 above warns about ‚Äî let the FK constraint catch it instead. Use
  this pattern only when the caller needs actual data from the other
  domain, not just its existence.

## Adding One Endpoint ‚Äî `generate method`

```bash
go-scaffold generate method <domain> <name> --type <get|post|put|patch|delete> [--get-mode all|one] [--field <name>]
```

Patches `handler.go`/`service.go` (and `repository.go` + the `repository`
interface + its `fakeRepo` test stub, for a `get --get-mode one --field`
lookup) in place, at the `// go-scaffold:*` marker comments near the end of
each file. **Don't delete those markers** ‚Äî they're where the next
`generate method` call inserts. The method body is always left as a `TODO`
that compiles and returns a clean `500` (`apperror.NewInternal()`) rather
than guessing at business logic ‚Äî same spirit as `generate module`'s
placeholder fields.

## Testing Conventions

- Unit and integration tests live in the same directory as the code under
  test (Go convention) ‚Äî never a separate `test/` folder. `test/` is only
  for e2e black-box suites or fixtures.
- `service_test.go` uses a fake repository ‚Äî no DB required, always runs.
- `handler_test.go` runs against a real Postgres instance inside a
  transaction that's rolled back after each test ‚Äî skips automatically if
  the DB isn't reachable.

